Certainly! Below is an example of how you can create a causal graph with hidden confounding using TikZ in LaTeX. This graph includes observed covariates \( X \), hidden confounders \( U \), treatment \( T \), and outcome \( Y \). The direct edges represent causal relationships, while the bidirectional edge between \( U \) and \( Y \) indicates possible correlation due to the hidden confounder.

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric, arrows.meta}

\tikzset{
    block/.style = {rectangle, draw=black, fill=white, text width=6em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=3em},
    line/.style = {draw, thick, -Stealth},
    cloud/.style = {draw=red, ellipse, minimum width=8em, minimum height=4em, node distance=3cm},
    confounder/.style = {cloud, draw=blue, fill=lightblue},
    covariate/.style = {block, draw=green, fill=lightgreen},
    outcome/.style = {block, draw=orange, fill=yellow!50},
    treatment/.style = {block, draw=brown, fill=brown!20}
}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]

\node (X1) [covariate] {$X_1$};
\node (X2) [covariate, right of=X1] {$X_2$};
\node (T) [treatment, below of=X1] {$T$};
\node (U) [confounder, above of=T, xshift=-1cm] {$U$};
\node (Y) [outcome, below of=T] {$Y$};

\path [line] (X1) -- (T);
\path [line] (X2) -- (T);
\path [line] (U) -- (T);
\path [line] (U) -- (Y);
\path [line, <->] (Y) -- (U);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**:
  - `covariate`: Represents observed covariates \( X_1 \) and \( X_2 \).
  - `treatment`: Represents the treatment \( T \).

